For this project, I developed an STM32-based distance measurement system that uses an HC-SR04 ultrasonic sensor to measure the distance to nearby objects and display the result on a four-digit seven-segment display. The system updates measurements every 0.5 seconds, allows the user to toggle between centimeters and inches with a button press, and transmits distance readings to a serial terminal over USART.

I implemented the project using bare-metal CMSIS and PlatformIO, utilizing SysTick for periodic distance measurements, TIM2 for display multiplexing, and an additional hardware timer to accurately measure the ultrasonic echo pulse width. The project strengthened my experience with sensor interfacing, interrupt-driven programming, timer peripherals, serial communication, real-time data processing, and embedded system design.
